Sep 17 2009 	Remarkably quiet but drop breadcrumbs to your room.	I was booked into the Tuscany Suites and Casino as part of an event of about 800 people. The property is fairly new and, unlike many Vegas headliner hotels, is on the small side. It's conveniently located just east of The Strip on Flamingo, behind the Paris, Planet Hollywood and next to the Platinum, all of which loom over it. One of the Tuscany's draws for me was that its Casino is in a separate, but adjoining building. Therefore one is spared the cacaphonous ringing racket of slot machines, etc. encountered at most Vegas properties. There is a &quot;main&quot; building where one registers and finds several meeting rooms, a bar, and a high-end Italian restaurant of fairly good quality (the osso bucco was enormous and tasty as were the accompanying appetizers, bread, etc.). The rooms themselves are in 15 smaller, outlying buildings of 2-3 floors each identified by a letter. Herein lies the rub. The signage at the hotel is not particularly helpful, nor is the front desk staff because they are obviously familiar with the lay-out of the place and give superficial, fast directions. The xeroxed map is of little help either. For a first-timer, it can be confusing and vexing to find not only your building but the entrance closest to its elevator. The rooms are very spacious. My bathroom had loose faux-Tuscan tiles on the floor, a separate bath and shower, and a plentitude of towels, good toiletries, etc. The room's art work was neither Tuscan nor Vegas themed. It might have been the Amalfi coast, but that's only a stab. There's a sink, 2 electric burners, a mini-fridge and some rooms have microwaves (not mine). However they are of little use since there isn't one piece of cutlery, plates, cups, nor glasses (unless you count the - groan! - flimsy plastic ones) provided. There was a couch and easy chair but both are so low that it practically takes a crane to get you out. And, as with many hotels, there is woefully inadequate lighting by which to do any work or reading after sundown. Key cards are only good for one's own building and room. Therefore, if you invite someone from another building to your room, you were obligated to meet them at the building's (correct) entrance. The housekeeping staff were exemplary. The patio outside the main building is &quot;misted&quot; and the pool is good-sized. There's a good snack shop adjacent to the pool and the Casino has an adequate 24 hour restaurant. I was dismayed to learn that the hotel's on-line rate during my event was significantly lower than the convention rate I paid. That may have been the fault of the envent organizers. Caveat emptor!	
Sep 14 2009 	Stayed Here Again Liked It Again	I stayed here on a weekday in May 2009 for $18 on Hotwire. This time around, I didn't see a Hotwire description that matched the property, but I found a $22 rate online; however, a $10-per-stay resort fee has been added; still a better deal than per-day resort fees elsewhere. The other reviews and photos speak for themselves, but I want to say that my encounters with the front desk staff, maids and engineer (to replace the battery in the free room safe) were all positive during both stays. Perhaps this was due to my being there on slow days, or perhaps it was due to my being polite with them. If you're very budget-minded like me, consider getting the $4 24-hour pass on the local buses. Even if you arrived by car, you may find it convenient to use the frequent service on Flamingo two stops to Caesar's or Bellagio, or the half-hourly service on Koval to get to Circus Circus, Fashion Show Mall or Mandalay Bay. One night, I rode the Flamingo bus all the way east to play $2 blackjack with surrender at the Longhorn and pick up some groceries at Wal-Mart.Tip: If you are very concerned about security, make sure that the four outer doors to your particular building lock properly after closing. Consider, though, that in most hotels, anybody can enter the hallways.Finally, check out the Tuscany's fitness center and second pool / hot tub; more than you'd expect from hotels charging twice as much.	
