Aug 9 2009 	Some Room Renovations Were Better Than Others	We spent a total of ten, count ‘em,* ten* nights at the Tuscany, primarily for the same annual convention we attended last year. (See previous review.) Not much had changed in the casino, besides swapping out a few slots, or elsewhere on the common grounds. However, there were some updates in the room that left us with some mixed feelings.The sofa, chair and bedding had all been replaced which was fine. However, the kitchen area renovations were hit or miss. There was a faux marble countertop installed which was good. However, it came at the cost of the formerly full-sized refrigerator which was replaced by a smaller version that fit under the countertop. Also, the microwave that used to be there was now only available by request. Fortunately, it was not a problem to acquire one. My only complaint would be regarding the fitness center which I discovered on this trip. Besides the fact it’s a large, underutilized space, many of the moderate-sized dumbbells – 20 to 35 lbs. – were missing, which effectively cut my workout options. However, the laundry room, located in the same building, was a nice convenience.If you like the idea of the space of the Venetian but don’t want to pay the premium, then you’ll find the Tuscany to be a low-key alternative whose off-Strip location is closer to many Strip properties than its upscale Italian “sister”.	
