Jul 31 2009 	TSC: Such a deal	I travel frequently to Vegas, usually during the week, when hotel rates are much cheaper. My brother had recommended the Tuscany Suites and Casino (TSC) to me; it's where he usually stays in Vegas, and when Expedia came up with a $22/night rate for my dates (20 to 23 July), I decided to book it. I generally prefer the glitz, glitter, and buzz of the Strip hotels, but I'm always willing to give a recommended place a try, especially at a bargain price. In this case, I'm glad I did. TSC is an excellent value, with comfortable rooms, friendly staff, user-friendly layout, and easy parking.I was given a nonsmoking king room on the second floor of the &quot;I&quot; building. The room was decent, with a separate sitting area and, as other TA reviewers have noted, a minifridge and coffee maker. I found the room to be similar to but larger than rooms I've seen at various Holiday Inns, Comfort Inns, etc. over the years. The furnishings were a bit worn and not high quality, but at $22/night, I have no real complaint. The A/C was an older-style floor unit but worked well. The bathroom was the most pleasant surprise: large, with a separate shower stall and bathtub. Fancy -- sort of.I had trouble sleeping my first night, after getting in late and hearing my upstairs neighbors thumping and bumping around -- not unusual for a motel- or garden apartment- style &quot;resort&quot;. The noises resumed fairly early in the morning, and when I called the front desk to ask about a possible room change (to something on the third, or top, floor of TSC), the operator abruptly said, &quot;I'll have security check it out.&quot; Maybe 10 minutes later, I had a call, and &quot;Security&quot; said they'd visited the room above mine and found it empty (speculating, as I did, that the party had stayed up late and then checked out early). I slept for a couple more hours and then called the front desk again to ask about a room change. The woman who answered said, &quot;No problem; we'll hold another unit for you on the 3rd floor of the H Building.&quot; I went down to reception, and I received my new room keys. The new room was an improvement in several ways: newer A/C; recently renovated furnishings -- including a smart new bed treatment with a duvet and even accent pillows worthy of the MGM Grand's West Wing rooms -- and...quieter than my first room. I called the front desk to thank them again.TSC's location and parking are also strong points. It's on E. Flamingo, a few blocks from the Strip. One problem -- nothing to do with TSC per se -- is that E. Flamingo, like many of Vegas's busier roads, is undergoing major repairs, which makes access to the hotel a bit more difficult than usual, especially at night. But once at TSC, parking is free, easy, and plentiful, with no long walks to your room.The &quot;Beach Cafe&quot; -- located next to the pool and adjacent to the casino and hotel reception -- is convenient for snacks and drinks and not too expensive. Their personal pizzas are a true Vegas dining bargain, tasty and cheap -- especially the meat lover's, with more meat than one should eat, for $4.50. I didn't use the pool at the TSC -- I rarely do at Vegas hotels; too hot and crowded, and I prefer the ocean for swimming -- but it was fairly big and looked alright. The internet, as other reviewers have noted, is free in wifi form in some areas of the hotel (lobby, Beach Cafe, around the pool) but costs pretty much the same as other Vegas hotels for in-room connection via wifi or cable. Again, given the room rate I was paying, I can't complain. I used the free wifi in the available areas; it worked pretty well most but not all of the time.I gamed some in the TSC's casino; it was alright. The slots were neither the loosest nor tightest I've experienced in Vegas. If nothing else, the casino here was a good adult respite from all the kids elsewhere on the property.Conclusion: TSC is a great value, and for the most part, it's a fairly nice property. It's neither luxurious nor peaceful, but there are scores of other hotels and resorts to fill those needs. TSC is very kid- and family-friendly while at the same time providing good, solid, and reasonably quiet accommodations for solo travelers like me. I'd recommend staying here and spending the savings on wining, dining, and gambling on the Strip.	
