Oct 13 2008	hidden costs	Where as most basic hotels these days will provide free internet in the rooms, the Tucany will charge you 13.95 for 24 hrs of time. This is absurd if you just wanted to say, check on a flight or such.I also used the biz center to print boarding passes, There is a per minute charge for this after finding one computor that would not work while the clock was running ,it cost me 7 bucks to print a couple of passes. When checking out the next morning I found out that they charge 20 per night extra for 3 people in the room.When I asked for a supervisor they said that none where on duty, they finally called a Pit boss who was not aware how the hotel was run. He said sorry to bad,The internet and biz center are run by and outside company so if somthing goes wrong Tucany is no help. I would not recommend the Tucany	
Oct 8 2008 	Warning!	Honestly, after reading other reviews, I cooled off a little. People love this place and there were definately things to love about it. However I have serious complaints and just want to warn those of you in a similar situation. I am a hotel manager in Oregon, so I know a few things. For one, I was here for a conference for my hotel chain and my company arranged to pay for my room with a credit card and sent an authorization. As I always do, I called ahead and everything was in place. When I arrived, I told the lady they had authorization on a company card, but here's mine for incidentals. She told me they would authorize $10 on my card. She then handed me my card back saying they only had authorization to charge my company card one night, their computer said &quot;guest pays&quot; and she had already authorized my card $280 for the rest of my stay! Without even giving me a chance to straighten it out. She then told me I would have to see the concierge. My front desk staff is empowered to help our guests. They do not have to stand in line to see someone else. After a long wait, the concierge told me they didn't have authorization and they would not accept a faxed one now as they don't accept them past 72hrs prior to arrival. Even though THEY lost it. She further went on to say she would not call my company to straighten out the problem, I would have to figure out something. At my property, if we misplace an authorization, we are on the phone doing everything we can to get our guest comfortably into their room asap. we do not look at them in a strange town with no bed and say, sorry, good luck to ya! It turned out, my Controller had to drive to my bank and deposit money into my bank account.The front desk charges $12 for early check in. What is this! Unheard of is what it is. I heard the front desk clerk tell a guest (who is also a frequent traveler and never heard of such a thing) it was because house keeping has to come in early to clean the rooms for him. Wrong. Housekeeping starts at 8 or 9 am, sometimes as early as 7am, some larger hotels have them around the clock. If you have a room ready, you do what you can to accomodate your guests. Then, from my room, I used a 1-800 number calling card to call my company and my hotel property quite a few times in the 5 days I was there. There is nothing on the phone telling you EVERY call you make has a $1.00 charge. When I checked out I was horrified. Outrageous! The front desk clerk went to get a manager (once again, he was not empowered to do anything) Another guy came out and said &quot;It's only a dollar&quot; For one thing, that's rude and unprofessional, for another, it was only $1.00 forty times, for another thing, if it's only a dollar, you take it off my bill! I told him no hotel charges that and he asked what other hotels I stay at! Again, very rude, beside the point. However I told him I stay in hotels, nice ones, a minimum of 5 times per year. I then asked if the casino wasn't making enough money for them, that they had to nickel and dime their guests to death. He shrugged. One more thing. From our room, we ordered a $20 pizza. When it was delivered, it was $30. The guy said there was a $3.00 delivery fee, fine, we saw that on the brocure. But there is also a $6.95 surcharge. For what??? I asked if that is charged in the restaurant, he said no, only for delivery. For what, gas? The restaurant is located in the casino! We sent the pizza back and a lady who barely spoke english called us in our room to chew us out and said if you don't want the pizza, don't order it! I told her we'll take the $20 pizza we ordered, not the $30 no explanation pizza.Finally, we were in building M, which is a hike to the casino and the conference rooms where my meetings were.All of that said, except for one bartender, all of the personell were very friendly and accomodating (except front desk and management). althought our matress was old and badly worn, the room was clean and spacious and had a micro/fridge, sink and range! I wish I had known, we would've brought food to cook! How fun. So if you stay here, you could plan to do that. And if you like poker, Texas Hold Em, the pool room here is exceptional. Wonderful staff and a fabulous local crowd. They made our stay great, in particular my husband who played with them while I was in meetings.However, though we will return to this poker room, on my company's next conference, we will not stay at this hotel due to the service we received. We were previously at the Wynn and the Westin and had none of the above issues.	
