Jun 10 2008 	Next Time Someplace Else	Checked out yesterday. I noticed the mixed reviews ahead of time, and in general I agree with the accuracy of remarks, both good and bad. I accompanied my husband to a 3 day convention here. The hotel would not allow coffee urns in the meeting rooms; they wanted people to leave (therefore missing part of) their workshops to go elsewhere to buy coffees. Tuscan Gardens restaurant is okay, and pricey: no modest sized side salads included; we had to pay about 7 bucks a la carte for an unnecessarily generous salad to accompany our platters.We stayed in Building L. Upon arriving we got maintenance to come immediately to replace the smoke detector battery, which was chirping. He also did something right away about the stall shower door, which kept popping ajar. Near the end of our 5 night stay, it was popping open again. We did not rest well. We could hear people &quot;stomping&quot; around on the 3rd floor above us early in the morning and also late at night. The bed was soft and saggy, made up with thin bed sheets. After awhile I got used to the sound of the jet planes taking off from the airport, but if I woke up too early, between the saggy bed, foot-stomping coming from above, and the jets taking off every few minutes, I couldn't fall back to sleep. Our a/c unit was quiet enough, but when walking outside we noticed another unit whining away in an irritating fashion.Both our bath fans whined at a very high pitch that made us feel frazzled - the one in the water closet and the other in the main bathroom. The coarseness of our first roll of no-frills, unbleached toilet paper in our room had us making jokes about planing logs; all the public rest rooms on The Strip used a better quality. Fortunately our 2nd roll of white paper was a little bit better.If you are reasonably physically fit, dress cool, and can take some heat for a short walk, it's not far to the rear of air-conditioned Bally's Hotel and Casino, where you can hop on the air-conditioned Monorail. That has 7 stations, from the MGM Grand at the south end, to the Sahara Hotel and Casino, up north by the Stratosphere. The Monorail isn't cheap but it saves you a huge amount of time getting around. And you'll have more energy to enjoy your day or evening longer.	
Jun 7 2008 	For an off-strip hotel good location	On a midweek stay in the summer, the big-name hotels on the strip offer prices comparable to the Tuscany. I'd rather stay in one of those. But for much of the year, and on weekends, Tuscany would be a great value.ASSETS: Rooms are huge. In addition to size of room, mine had both a bath and shower, and toilet behind a separate door. Clean, with good housekeeping staff. Good refrigerator, with ice machine down the hall that worked. You can park near your building, which is impossible on the Strip, and nice if you're traveling with lots of gear. Nice pool area without crowds. A very friendly and helpful staff. Very nice landscaped grounds. 24 hour restaurant in the casino with tasty but not fancy food. Unexpectedly, a gorgeous wedding chapel.WEAKNESSES: Two stove burners, but NO MICROWAVE, and not so much as a spoon. Very limited room service menu. Limited cable had only CNN, WGN, TBS, and local stations. Wi-Fi is available only by paying an extra daily charge. These may be minor considerations to some travelers, but may be significant to others who might deliberately choose a suite hotel.LOCATION: This was very important to me. It's about a ten minute walk to the Strip and to the Monorail. And at the Strip, you're at the convergence of Bally's, Paris, Bellagio, Caesar's, and the Flamingo. A great location. You can do a lot within walking distance. Flamingo Road has a sidewalk, and pedestrian crossings, but it is basically a concrete canyon with a six-lane highway and car exhaust running through it. You may encounter a panhandler or a drunk or prostitute on your walk over to the Strip. For a big city person, this is nothing, but it may frighten someone from a more sheltered background. You can always take a cab. Not far from the airport, either. My cab to the hotel from the airport was $13.50 plus tip. My shuttle back to the airport was $5.00 plus tip.	
Jun 6 2008 	Great one night stay!	After some vacation time in LA, I needed a hotel to stay on Memorial Day eve before I flew out of Vegas early the next day. Based on the reviews here and cost, I chose the Tuscany Suites &amp; Casino. I got a rate of $39 ($45 w/taxes/fees) on i4vegas.com. What a deal it turned out to be! I arrived after dark, around 9:30pm. The hotel is easy to find, just off the strip. Check in went smoothly and it was relatively easy to find my “L” building in the sprawling, multi-building complex. However once I did find the entrance, my room key did not work to open the door. I tried the 2nd key with no luck. So I walked all the way around the building looking for another entrance. Luckily there was one on the other end and one of my keys worked just fine (the other room key was “dead”). It was just a hassle hauling luggage in the dark after I had been on the road for 4.5 hours. Then it turns out my room was only two doors away from the “broken” entrance so re-entering the building to my room was not convenient. But the room/suite itself was wonderful! It was clean, well maintained and very large, even larger than the Rio which I had stayed at earlier in the week; see that review for details. The refrigerator was much bigger than dorm size but not full size; I’d call it “under the counter” size. There were no in room dishes or microwave but I was able to find some at the “coffee shop” on site which was still open and they let me use them to heat up leftovers. The bathroom was also clean, well maintained and huge. It contained a separate toilet room, a shower stall and separate bath tub; very nice! The shower water pressure and temperature were excellent. I requested a non-smoking king bed room, which I received. The room/suite also had a couch, chair, coffee table and kitchen table with two chairs. There was plenty of room for 4 people. The heat/cool unit was a wee bit loud and not very accurate; I set it to 70 but if felt more like 65 so I adjusted it accordingly. But it did work quickly to heat/cool the room and kept it comfortable once I determined my desired temperature. I was placed on the first floor of a multi-floor building and did see someone leave the room next to me but the room was sound proof enough that I did not hear anyone, ever. The bed and linens were comfortable and I slept just fine.I had to leave early the next morning so I was not able to use the rest of the complex to comment on other areas such as the pool, restaurants, casino, etc. It did appear to be clean, well maintained, walkable to the strip, and it is very convenient to the airport. If I am ever in Vegas again, I will most definitely consider a stay here again. Except for the broken building entrance door, a perfect night’s stay at an excellent price!	
Jun 3 2008 	Not bad for the price	Stayed here as part of a conference for 3 nights. The rooms are VERY large, and could easily fit a huge group of people (for a college group). Although there's a small fridge and stove, there are no pans/pots/plates in the room, and no microwave which is a definite downside. Limited tv channels and old tv, but it works fine. There's a nice lounge area/ couch on one side of the room, and a dining set near the kitchen. The rooms are divided into different buildings (A,B,C, etc), so your room key allows entry into your building, and then into your room. However, a big concern about safety was that it apparently is easy to get into the building without a key, since during the time we were there multiple restaurants managed to sneak in and leave their menus under the door to our room. Called hotel security about this, but apparently it happens all the time so be wary. About a 10-15 minute walk to the strip. The location is fine, near the Westin and Bally's, and around the corner there's a 7-11. If you plan on gambling at the hotel, join the Player's Club, since you'll get about $5 free slot play to pass the time. There are A LOT of penny slot machines, and it seemed a pretty popular place for the older crowds. Decent selection of places to eat, including Mexican food at The Cantina. The hotel had a buy-one-get-one-free coupon, which made the cost of dinner for two fajitas about $12. There's also a Lawry's directly across the street, and more restaurants eastt of the strip on Flamingo (Roy's, Morton's), which is great if you want to eat elsewhere and avoid the strip traffic. Overall, a decent experience (especially for the price), and would stay again.	
