nd they were pretty good. One more comment, for families, the rooms usually have two double beds -- we think they are way too small for adults to be comfortable, and this is really unnecessary since the rooms are large enough to accomodate two Queens. This is a major complaint for us. That is why we booked the King room with the Queen sofa sleeper for the kids. They normally don't put mattress pads on the sofa bed mattresses &amp; they are all stained up &amp; gross. I wouldn't ever go back.Nancy	
Dec 24 2007 	Budget Bellagio	This place is a GREAT value. We paid $35/night for mid-week. The room was very large, w/coffee maker, fridge, microwave &amp; stove. Bath was big, with separate bath, shower, &amp; toilet &quot;room&quot;. Nothing fancy, but clean and in working order. Great place for an extended stay. The place was much nicer than we expected for the price. Some reviewers had complained about &quot;smell&quot; but we didn't notice any problems there. Our interactions with the staff were all good. The place is very nicely landscaped, some good food bargains (2.99 steak &amp; eggs and .99 pancakes from midnight to 5 am!), and an adequate casino. It even has a good exercise room and lap pool. And it's only a long block from the strip. There were some small problems--only one elevator per building, and ours was at the other end of the building. Would rather take the stairs, but there was no outside entrance for either stairwell. The construction of the buildings seems shoddy--kind of looks like a cheaply made group of college dorm buildings: Think Best Western meets faux-Tuscan villa. But for that price, this place is a find. If you'd rather spend your travel money on something other than a room--how much time do you spend in it anyway?--this place is for you.	
Dec 22 2007 	Another great stay at the Tuscany	Just returned from our second stay at the Tuscany (5 nights), and it was a pleasant experience. We had requested a 3rd floor suite, because, as with any multi-level hotel, we didn't want the risk of heavy-footed noise above us. The room was in Bldg &quot;B&quot; which faces Flamingo Rd. For those sensitive to traffic noise, you may want to consider another building. Being city folks, we are immune to it :-)The room was convenient and clean; I believe it was a recently renovated one. We had a small stove top and micro-wave. The refrigerator seemed to be working overtime, as it froze our beverages no matter what setting we had it on. Because my husband takes insulin (requiring refrigeration), we called the front desk to inquire about the settings. When informed of the problem, a maintenance man showed up immediately, and they were so kind as to completely change out the unit.The pool area remains closed for repairs right now.Not much luck playing slots, but the casino is always fun.As always, Marilyn's cafe offered decent food at reasonable prices; and the Mexican cantina offered same. Did not visit Tuscany Gardens this time.We would like to thank: Alina at the front desk, Ruth, the concierge, and the lovely Suzanne who served cocktails, for their gracious and kind service.See you next year!	
Dec 17 2007 	Accessible room nice place to stay	We stayed at Tuscany 12-11 thru 12-15 in a wheelchair accessible room. I booked directly because the various travel websites cannot guarantee me an accessible room The bathroom was roomy and had both a seperate shower (without access) and a tub with an attached flip up bath bench. No curtain on the tub but there is a handheld shower. Be aware that the bath bench is somewhat low and there is no mechanism to make it higher so if bad hips are a problem that could be too low. Sink is open at the bottom (no vanity to block a wheelchair) and the toilet is standard height but has wall bars as usual. I still needed to assist my mother to go to the bathroom but I expect that when away from home.The room itself was spacious and clean. Request a microwave on arrival and you can get some things from a grocery store (about a mile down Flamingo there is an Albertsons) to make quick breakfasts and late nite snacks! Buy water too since a bottle in the machine was 1.50. My refrigerator was missing a leg and so it rocked a little--I suppose they would have brought a new one but I did not ask. My hair dryer in the bathroom was shorting out and was replaced that day. There are no kitchen supplies except some cups so plan on getting or bringing some flatware and paper plates if you plan to eat in the room. Cups are foam and plastic (for all of you who have recently seen news reports of hotels using glass and improperly cleaning them). Coffee makers in room are 4 cuppers and the coffee pods were tasty.Beds: Comfy and clean. Mom's was a little short sheeted- maybe an inch or two but no big deal. Pillow were fluffy. The only thing I will say about the bed are is that since this was an accessible room, it would have been nice to have a rail on the wall by the bed to hold on for balance--the hanger rack was there and is not a secure device to hold onto (never is--don't try it at home either!). Service was about average. No rudeness but I didn't see anyone going out of the way for us either. Our flight was cancelled so they did give me an extra hour grace on checkout. Maids respected the do not disturb signs. Several did not speak English but we got along with hand signs and motions.Coupon wise, at check-in, you get a packet and also one when you sign up in the casino. Our free souvenir was dice. Casino was smaller but adequate and they were kind enough to wait until after midnite to keep the player club open so my niece who turned 21 could get her card.This hotel in relation to the strip is a bit long if you are disabled but if you can handle the 3 block walk it is fine. It was just a little long to do in a chair so we took the car place to place. Be aware that the hotel is actually several buildings on the land which are connected by cement paths but are outdoors. To get to the main desk and casino/restaurants, you need to go outside. Security is maintained in the indiviual buildings by use of your room card to gain access.We only sampled Marilyns Cafe for food but it was good. Steak and lobster was 10.99 on Tuesday--lobster small but very sweet.Anyways, for us the main things are cleanliness, good disabled accessiblity and a comfy bed. Tuscany has all 3.	
Dec 5 2007 	Our Fourth Stay at the Tuscany	My husband and I stayed at the Tuscany for nine days in early November. This was our sixth trip to Las Vegas and our fourth stay at the Tuscany. We have never been disappointed. A few things we do to make our stay more enjoyable: We always request a room in a building located near the lobby. The reason is that we often stay late in the casino and feel safer not having to walk too far to our room. To avoid noise caused by guests living above us, we ask for a room on the third (top) floor. A nice feature is that the windows have screens and can open.The casino has a good selection of slot machines and tables. We have never had a problem getting served a drink even playing at the penny slot machines. Marilyn’s is good for a quick meal, but if you really want a bargain, go to Ellis Island and either eat in the restaurant or the Brewery. We love the chicken and ribs and draft beer at the Brewery. For less than $20 you will be able to have more food and beer than anywhere else. The restaurant at Ellis Island serves great food at considerably less cost than the Tuscany. We always make a point of going to the Tuscany Gardens on each visit. We use our Players’ Cards points and have always had a great meal. We also, make a point of going to Batista’s Hole in the Wall (one block from the strip) where you get the wine included with your meal. We have never had any problem getting loungers at the pool area. Drinks and food are near by. Nice music is always playing. There is also a great fitness area. However, I have noticed on my last three visits that the cardio machines are in various states of disrepair and most of the TVs are not working. However, it is a large facility that has a lap pool and Jacuzzi attached to it.	
