Oct 16 2007 	SMELLY	Having lived in Las Vegas previously, I was familiar with the casino but had never stayed in the hotel. We were in Building N. FIRST thing you notice when you walk in is the OVERPOWERING smell of probably whatever is sprinkled on the carpet or whatever is being used to mask odors. It is so very strong and not at all pleasant. Funny thing is you don't smell it as strongly in the room. The room has lots of room to move around. The kitchenette is adequate however, this hotel is advertised as &quot;suites&quot;. Usually that means you will also have at least basic dishes/pans/table ware etc. There are NONE of these items. So if you are planning to stay there because you are interested in being able to prepare basic meals, you can forget it. Unless you plan to travel with your own place settings and cookware or buy it there, you can find several other hotels in the area with stocked kitchenettes. We asked about even dish soap and a dishrag/towel and were told, &quot;use your bath towels&quot;. On the first night, we called for additional towels/shampoo and were directed to the housekeeping line which was NOT answered but a machine said to leave your request and it would be handled. Nope again. No one even responded much less came to the room with towels or shampoo. I would never stay at this hotel again. It's overpriced considering it's not on the strip and too far for walkers to get to the strip, customer service is not what it should be and there is an unpleasant smell. You can do much better in Las Vegas.	
Oct 8 2007 	Jewelry Stolen by Cleaning Staff	Several family members met up in Vegas and stayed at this hotel. During one of the morning cleanings, a necklace and earrings stolen right off the table. This was not costume jewelry, it was the real deal. We were told to file a report with the security booth. The first security personnel we approached was extremely rude and was talking to us as though they were the victims when I asked him what his procedure was for taking this issue up with their cleaning crew. His rude response was &quot;there's theft at all Vegas hotels.&quot; Shortly into filing the theft report, we were approached by another security guard who was much more pleasant to deal with and did feel bad about the situation. Obviously we will not see this jewelry again, however, we plan on following the progress of our theft report to be sure that someone is held accountable.As far as the rooms are concerned, they are not what I consider suites; they are just larger rooms with a very small sink and table. The carpet was nasty, the comforters were nasty and the bathroom floors were filthy. We had a 1st floor room and it sounded like the folks in the room above us were going to come through the ceiling as they walked around.Also, it was a nightmare trying to close the room to the door. For some reason the deadbolt lock kept getting stuck in the lock position, so closing the door took quite a while to figure out. Other family that stayed here had the exact same problem with their lock – the only way they were able to figure it out was due to some hotel staff walking by.Really, the only good thing I can say about this hotel was that the service at the cafe was good and the hotel is in a good location. Because of all the Vegas options for rooms, I would NOT recommend this hotel!	
Oct 6 2007 	Great off-strip Hotel	We spent 7 days/six nights in Vegas in the middle of August. First time at the Tuscany and we loved it. Arrived Saturday afternoon and had a 20 minute line at the front desk. I hate waiting, but this wasn't too long compared to some of the hotels on the strip. Huge room and very quiet, We thought we were the only guests on the floor. They must be remodeling the rooms because every morning they were unloading a new delivery of furniture in the parking lot in front of the fitness center.  Both of the pools were nice, and the lap pool was ours alone most of the time. The table games in the casino were a little slow, not a lot of play. But with the strip a few blocks away, we didn't mind. We tried all of the restuarants with the exception of the Mexican one. Good food with large servings. And the Tuscan themed restuarant was staffed by actual Italians, didn't expect that. And around the corner is the Ellis Island restuarant with very good $4.99 steak dinners.While the walk to the strip isn't too bad, we did have a car and used it to get to the far end of the strip, downtown and up the the mountains. I plan on staying at the Tuscany Suites my next trip to Las Vegas.	
