May 30 2007 	Okay for off strip hotel	We stayed for 2 nights at the end of April. Although the hotel looks nice at first, the rooms have a motel feel. Check-in was easy, as we arrived late on a Friday. The complex is large with multiple buildings. We stayed at the northernmost end (D)? Clientele in this hotel mostly appeared to be 50+ years, although we did see some college/high school sports teams at the hotel.The room was on the bottom floor, and smelled slightly musty. It was large, with king size bed and scant pillows. Not the most comfortable sleep (but then who's sleeping in Vegas?) The TV had about six channels, no cable or satellite, and at least two channels dedicated to gambling or the hotel. Not much to watch. Also, there was no hotel guide in our room, so we had no idea of the amenities, closing times, or if room service existed.Bathroom: separate toilet/ sink room. Noisy ventilation &amp; plumbing. Our toilet was plugged before we got there. The problem was fixed the next day (we didn't feel like hanging around all night). The shower was okay, but the shower head is too short for 6' tall people. Toiletries are minimal and very basic.Kitchenette: Coffee machine WOULD have been great had they actually put enough creamer packages for two people. I even left a note requesting an additional creamer, but this request was ignored. So we decided to skip the coffee the second day.Pool: big, inviting, very busy early on Saturday morning. Didn't actually swim, but plenty of other guests did.Food: Tuscany Gardens Italian: The veal with mushroom sauce was saltier than I normally like. Otherwise the food was good. Ambience was not very romantic, since right across the hall, the bar was really rocking. Beachfront Coffee has hardly anything to accompany a cup of coffee for breakfast. Go elsewhere.Location: yes, it is 2 LONG blocks from the strip. Realize that walking the strip is something that most people spend the day doing and know that you will be tired. A day pass for the monorail is useful to go back and forth. Discount coupons are in many of the Las Vegas guides you pick up. However, there will still be more walking from the station/to the station - there's always a casino you will have to go through. The walk along Flamingo from the strip is not very pretty (empty lots, a little rundown), but was safe enough. Bottom Line: We will try a hotel on the southern strip next time. The price is right, but if you're spending all your time on the strip, staying there will save you time. The quality at Bally's (previous visit) was much better than this place.	
