Jun 22 2006	Great stay	Stayed here for 3 nts and loved it. Huge room with refridgerator and coffee maker (unusual for Las Vegas). Short walk to the Strip or use the CAT bus.	
Jun 14 2006 	Improving but the price is creeping up	This is the third time I've stayed at this hotel. It's improved a bit since last year. I think the management has changed, and that's a good thing.In the rooms, they've given up on the kitchenette. That makes sense, because they never gave you pots, pans, dishes, or utensils. The bar sink, fridge, and microwave remain, as does the coffee pot.The empty space in the casino has been filled in with more stuff. The comedy club that was shuttered last year has been replaced with a poker room. They gave up on trying to do &quot;shows&quot; - noone comes to the Tuscany to see a show. There's a new sports bar with lots of TV's and friendly service.There's $3 blackjack most of the time, although it's multiple deck. Cocktail service in the casino is spotty. Some people can get drinks, but I never seem to be able to.The awful buffet line is gone from the coffee shop, and it's being replaced with a counter. The coffee shop has gotten a coat of paint. The service is spotty - most mornings, the breakfast crew was overwhelmed by the number of guests.The rooms remain well furnished, and are some of the largest I've ever stayed in. The comments below about reserving a non-smoking room and getting a smoking room are on target, as that happened to me. My room's air conditioning unit squeaked a lot and didn't cool well. They've added WiFi for a fee and it worked great.In a nutshell: this hotel is improving, and is usually a good value. The rates are creeping up, however. This hotel is a bargain under $100/night. Over $100/night, I'd rather stay somewhere else.	
