Jan 8 2006 	Easy Camping	Finally got around to writing the review now that it's post holiday. Accommodations were very nice. Staff try and make an effort to accommodate. Can't give excellent rating since this is not a full service hotel but it is well above average expectations for an extended stay type of hotel.Thanks to reviews on Trip Advisor, we were prepared for our stay. Brought a messkit for easy cooking in the kitchen. Hopped over to the corner gas/marts for snacks and easy cook stuff. Brought own hot drink mixes and &quot;add water&quot; breakfast kits so getting a quick breakfast in the morning made things fast and easy.Got convenient bus pass ($5? buy on board) and hopped aboard across the street. I agree with other reviewers that food at the resort is not something I want to spend money on. One crusty dry dinner at $30 each person was enough money wasted. Service was excellent but it doesn't satisfy hunger. Nor can I recommend the less than average packaged lunches from the breakfast shop. First bus stop at the Flamingo down the road and Caeser's are way better food options plus they have very pretty exotic birds to look at. The Paris casino seemed most moderate and convenient for an insomniac like me to get excellent crepes and french fare at any hour. Bus passes are good for 24 hours. If you eat at their streetside restaurant, outdoor seating gets you a front row view of the Bellagio fountains which was fantastic at night. Only 2-3 repeats of the same song during the company's 4 hour french dinner. Plus the human wildlife parading past on the sidewalks once nightlife starts kicking in is fairly interesting.Enjoyed the large suite and kitchenette. Pool was fine and jacuzii had wide range of jets and plenty of room. I recommend sport towels. Pool towels were quite rough and thin. Rooms are spacious, separate bath areas convenient and well lit. Having an upstairs apt/suite was great except for some construction for the first day in the hallway. The adjacent building under construction started their workday at 4am. After the first time, attitude was if you can't beat them, join them. Hence early morning exploration of the Paris casino since sleeping was out of the question. Since many of the casinos have a virtual outdoor theme, one can always pretend to be in some other country while taking in the amusement factor.Staff was friendly and accommodating. Overheard many guests note one or two things that needed fixing which the staff took care of although some required 2-3 attempts like keys in our building. Got to know neighbors since we had to help each other get into the building when keys didn't work.:+) hahahha. Only people who were actually rude were other guests trying to market their products while I was waiting in the lobby. This is not the Ritz, it's an extended stay hotel so guests should be able to manage for themselves to a certain extent. If you have a problem, then at least let staff know how they can help you resolve the problem. Bring a mess kit $5 to $10 or a microwavable kit $2 if you want to use the kitchenette. It can always be disposed or donated to a friend at the end of your stay. Note to Newbies, never use styrofoam to heat food in the microwave. Our stay here was for business with a little time off. I'd like to return and use this as a base of exploration. There is beatiful canyon country to explore within 20-45 minutes drive, tons of virtual exploration adventures within the city and other entertainment. One place close by lets people experience parachuting without having to jump out of a plane. Basically, a guest hovers over a jet engine so it feels like falling but it's safe.If you just want to experience dizziness, take in the 3D movies (10 min) at the M&amp;M Factory/Store Museum. Their rolling barrel of M&amp;Ms that you walk through to get to the theater is loads of tizzy dizzy fun. There were three very more than happy ladies singing and having a great time during my visit. It was a nice stop before returning to the hotel on the bus.Next time, an internet car rental will be taken care of first. During our stay here, a city event jacked up car rentals to 300% of normal pricing. That made us change plans to explore the canyon country since car rental was not practical. The hotel has a direct line to an airport rental agency which will pick up guests. Prices changed hourly. Alternatives are to hop over to the Flamingo down the very long block and rent a car directly from them and avoid airport tax.	
