Jun 12 2005	Luxury at a Reasonable Price	Our recent stay at the Tuscany was one of the most comfortable and relaxing we have had during any our of many visits to Las Vegas. It was my first time to stay at an off-strip, not well-known facility, so I was a little nervous at first. Upon arrival at the hotel, we were greeted by a friendly staff member, and from this point forward, everything fell into place. Our room was gorgeous. It was surprisingly large and beautifully furnished. Everything looked new and was very clean; it was as if we were the first people to have ever stayed in the room. The kitchenette was a huge plus, especially when it came to keeping drinks cold on a hot summer day.The hotel is a few short blocks from the strip. For someone not used to walking much, it could be too far for comfort, but for us, it was perfect as the hotel was close enough to the strip to enjoy the excitment of Las Vegas but far enough away to escape the omnipresent &quot;ding-ding-ding&quot; of slot machines. We could walk directly to the unit (through secured doors) without having to walk 10-15 minutes through a typical casino just to get to the guest elevators.A little secret is that you can enter the back of Bally's and then, in the comfort of air-conditioning, walk from Bally's to Paris (they connect) to get to the Aladdin and the strip. Moreover, you can catch the monorail, conveniently located at the back of Bally's, that will quickly take you to other parts of the strip. (The monorail runs every 5 minutes.)We were very happy with our experience at the Tuscany. I have a rule that I stay at a different hotel during every visit to Las Vegas, simply for the sake of having a new experience. In the case of the Tuscany, however, I am willing to let that rule slide and to book a room again. The Tuscany provided luxury and comfort for a reasonable price. If you're looking for a pleasant trip to Las Vegas without getting caught up in the hustle'n bustle of the strip, the Tuscany is a good choice.	
