May 31 2005	Great Place to Sleep - Just don't expect all the frills	Stayed at the Tuscany May 20 - 23, 2005. The location is pretty good for an off-the-strip hotel. About a block and a half from Las Vegas Blvd. and Flamingo. Pretty much right behind Bally's. The grounds are kept up pretty nicely. They do have a casino, but I would avoid it other than the bar for a quick drink before you go out. The casino is frequented by locals, so its not very exciting. The pool area is awesome - nice, clean pool, and poolside bar service. For 3 guys on a gambling trip, this pool was a welcome distraction. Plenty of drinks, girls in bikinis, and not too many kids. The only letdown was that there are not enough lounge chairs. You must get to the pool very early if you want to get a chair at all.The rooms themselves are very large suites. The one we had included two double beds, table and chairs, a couch, club chair, end tables, TV, and dresser. Very spacious and clean. The bathroom is nice as it has a separate room for the toilet while the shower, tub, and sink can be assessable to others. Everything was in good condition and in working order. The hallway of the building and the room itself did have a slightly unpleasant odor. Sort of like a strong orange chemical smell. The cleaning staff does not speak English well. I have stayed at strip hotels (Paris, NYNY, MGM) and found this hotel to be more relaxed and spacious... but remember, you ARE away from the action. If you want to be in the thick of things, I wouldn't recommend this hotel. I also would not recommend it if you do not have a car. Although only a block and a half from the Strip, IT IS A HIKE!! You do not want to do this walk several time per day. All in all, if you want a roomy place to relax between gambling and clubbing, and you have a car, this is the place. If you are looking for more excitement or to be where there is non-stop action, stay on the Strip.	
May 30 2005	Perfect for us!!!	We just came back from a 3 night stay at The Tuscany. This was my fifth time in Vegas, having stayed downtown and at Bally's. By far Tuscany is my favorite place to stay. We found it to be like two vacations in one. While at the pool area, you have absolutely no idea that you are just a few blocks from the strip. We only had one breakfast buffet there, which was not award winning, but very acceptable, espescially for under $6. We found the staff to be fine, the room was huge and clean!!! It is a few blocks from the strip, and although there is a bit of a wait at times for a taxi, it is still much easier to get one then at some of the larger casinos right on the strip. The grounds are well landscaped and cared for...very attractive!!! We will be going back, and will definitely recommend to friends. If you are looking for value, I can't imagine there is a better deal out there..oh yeah, if you are new to Vegas, keep your gambling downtown!!!	
May 20 2005	Loved the Tuscany!!!	My wife and I stayed here twice last year--first for her birthday, then for our wedding day. We loved it. We were new to Vegas, and the Tuscany was a perfect off-the-strip hotel. Quiet, secluded, with a nice pool, comfortable rooms and a very friendly staff. We were surrounded by European travelers, which gave an added dimension to the Mediterranean theme. Our first night, we ate at Marilyn's cafe (in the casino downstairs, open 24 hours) and, even though the service was absolutely terrible--we waited about half an hour before being greeted--it was still charming, and the collection of rangy Vegas &quot;types&quot; at nearby tables was definitely worth seeing. For the price, the Tuscany is great. If you're a high-rolling Vince Vaughn wannabe, stay at the Bellagio. But if you're looking for something inexpensive, quiet and clean, go to the Tuscany.	
May 17 2005 	Solid All Around	Just back from the Tuscany -- May 12th - 16th.I stayed here for $89/night which was a special rate arranged through a seminar I was attending. I would've preferred to stay on the strip, but for this rate on this weekend I couldn't pass it up. This hotel is about a 10-15 minute walk to the strip. I timed myself and it took me 8 minutes (I'm a quick walker) to get to the back of Bally's where you can enter near the Sports Book and then walk through Bally's to the strip if you want. Basically there are different 3 level buildings located all over the property, so you're in your own building.As for the rooms themselves ... they were great imho. Nothing super fancy, but very nice, clean, and VERY large. As said the bathroom is over-size as well with a separate shower and tub and separate door for the toilet as well. I am a single 30 year old, but if I had a family this hotel would be especially appreciated. The room is one big area -- full couch and chair opposite the side of the room from the bed(s). The TV is on a dresser along the wall b/t the windows b/t the bed and living area. The small kitchen area was right by the door and you're facing the TV as you walk in the room ... living area directly past the kitchen table and bathroom and bed to the right. It was nice having a small fridge for the waters I picked up at the nearby convenience store. The bed was fairly comfortable. 27&quot; TV had the networks, CNN, ESPN, WGN, and maybe TNT. Interactive channel (auto checkout, movies, internet) wasn't working any of the days I was there.The casino was very small relatively speaking and I didn't gamble at all. I had supper at the Tuscany Gardens (specializing in Italian) and it was adequate, but not great. I had received a $10 off an entree coupon upon check-in. Prices were very reasonable. I also twice ate at The Cantina, the Mexican restaurant in the casino area. It was adequate again, but not great. The beans that came with the complimentary chips and salsa were especially good for some reason. Had the breakfast buffet at Marylin's Cafe the last morning and it was just OK as well (eggs weren't very good), but very cheap at $5.95. All I wanted was a little bit, and it worked OK since I was in a hurry. Something off the menu may have been better. As mentioned there are other places nearby to eat like Lawry's, etc. There is a coffee shop/juice bar as well near the lobby/gift shop area.There was a pretty large complimentary workout room in the area where the lap pool and another jacuzzi is located. Nautilus machines, free weights and at least 4 treadmills/elliptical machines. The main pool area was very attractive as well ... although I didn't swim, I sat and had a drink while on the phone.In Review:If you know what you're looking for, the Tuscany Suites might be right up your alley. It would be a nice break from the hubbub on the Strip. If you don't mind some walking or aren't planning on being on the Strip every day this might be a good choice (especially considering price). The walking could get old. Also if you have family you would have more room to spread out and not feel cramped in the room. I would think this hotel would draw an older crowd the majority of the time ... not like senior citizen old, but the 35 and up crowd for sure. If you're up for big time gambling and poker, this isn't your place either. Would be good for a family stop in Vegas or a business traveler I'd think. If I was coming out to solely party, I would stay on the strip. For my situation it really did work out perfect.Positives:-- Price (even not at a special rate it's typically a bit less than 3-4 stars on the strip)-- Room size, cleanliness-- Relaxing (away from it all) mood-- Pool area-- Complimentary exercise room-- Separate lap pool and 2nd jacuzzi-- Relatively cheap drinks at the bar ($2.25 domestic bottle or so)Negatives:-- Food (was just OK)-- Walk to the Strip-- Cabs aren't AS plentifulI don't know if I'll stay there again b/c I generally don't go to Vegas for anything other than a big party, but if I was to go for business again or whatnot I wouldn't hesitate to stay again.	
May 16 2005	Too far and Too rude	My mother and I stayed at the Tuscany May 8-14 while at a conference. We were a bit dissappointed when we arrived. Although the Strip looks close, it is a bit of a walk - about 15 minutes. That gets you to Bally's or the Flamingo and then it's farther to anywhere else. The first guy that took our bags when we arrived in a taxi didn't offer to help and was rude when we asked him to take them. The front desk was cold and didn't seem too enthused that we were there - it may have been because we were at a reduced rate but that is no reason to treat us poorly. When we tried to get our bags brought to the room (all of the rooms are in separate buildings that you have to walk outside to get to), we called the bell desk 3 times and no one answered. We finally called the front desk and received our bags about 45 minutes after we had checked in. We ate in the cafe the first evening, and although the waiter was nice, the food was anything but. But I guess that's what you can expect from a 24 hour cafe. Maid service was good, but a little pushy to get the room cleaned. Very few of the staff spoke English which made it that much more difficult to communicate with them what we needed. Also, we are pretty sure someone entered our room on the first day we were out after it had been cleaned. We had come back in the morning after it was cleaned and left a light on. When we returned in the evening the light was off and the sink was partially filled with water. It cost about $10 to take a Taxi to and from the strip (Mirage, Mandalay Bay, Wynn). No shuttle service offered and they have to call for taxis. The players club is ok. It takes a few bucks to cash in for anything (at least over $150). The free souvenier was a deck of used playing cards from the casino. The slots were NOT loose! No one that I saw was winning. The slots at the airport are the best. Overall it was just ok. At least the rooms are big and very clean. Although there is a refrigerator and a stove, there is no microwave and no pots/pans/utensils to cook with. We tried heating up leftovers in metal containers on the stove but it started to smell like it would set off the fire alarm so we ate it cold. On checkout we were charged $10 extra for Friday night because the hotel was sold out - we tried to dispute this with the front desk but they said they couldn't help and we had to call the sales department - we are working on getting it straightened out with the conference people's help. The conference is moving to the Flamingo next time - we are really looking forward to that since it is on the strip. If you have a car and want a cheap rate at a clean hotel that is good for families this will work for you. If you want to mostly be on the strip and don't have a car I would suggest paying a little more to stay right on the strip - you'll save the money in taxi costs. Walking to the strip in daylight was fine, at night, not so much. I do have to add though, that there was a very polite and helpful Oriental man that made our vacation a little more enjoyable. He was the best staff person at the Tuscany.	
May 13 2005	Clean and Quiet 2 Blocks away from the Strip (near Bellagio/Caesar's)	We had 2 suites at Tuscany Suites, May 4-7, 2005. This hotel was recommended by a co-worker and I read the reviews off this website re: this hotel. So I was 95% comfortable booking it, but I was more anxious about check in times and room quality (quiet, clean etc).Check-in is at 3pm and we arrived at 230pm. Check-in was fast, there were about 2 ppl in front of me and 3 girls at the reception counter. We got the 3rd floor (very top floor) in a rear unit, facing away from the street. They don't have any adjoining suites, so we got ours right next to each other. The room was clean and huge. The bathroom was literally oversized..full bathtub and shower + toilet in diff. room w/ door. There was a total of 4 adults.. 2 in each room, so it was nice to have our space.I got these 2 suites thru expedia, their website indicated the rooms were sold out these dates. I requested 2 doubles in each room and got my request. I was worried they wouldn't fufill my request, but they did!The kitchnette had a mini fridge, table w/ 2 chairs, microwave, sink and plenty of cabinet space and a coffee maker w/ free coffee pouches. The TV was nice cuz we could turn it according to where we were in the room, we could watch tv from bed or from the sofa and chair/table they had.The other suite had a broken shower door, I called housekeeping and they told me to wait until a repairman showed up. We were on our way out and after waiting 10 mins, we just left. Turns out they did fix it when we got home. In our room, one of the lamps bulb's needed to be changed, but I didn't call for that since there was enough light.The AC is a bit noisy, wouldn't turn it on when we sleep, but we had it on low while we were out and about.The hotel is located about .5 miles from the strip, but I liked the location of the strip from us. we were on the end of teh strip that was closest to bellagion, caesar's, bally, wynn hotels. They are huge blocks, flat to walk on, but a trek, depending on what kind of shape you are in/heat factor. We did walk to the Wynn hotel and it took tops 25 mins. it was a good walk just to get some excercise in.across from the hotel was a Lawry's, and a japanese restaurant, Hamada of Tokyo, down the other street was PF Changs.. so they had good restaurants near by. I couldn't find a starbucks near there, but later heard there was one nearby, but kind of hidden. Oh wells, I still survived. I would definitely stay there again, since the property looked like it was no more than 3-5 yrs old. I didn't see any bugs. the parking was nice cuz you can park and walk right up to the bldg entrance, put your hotel card key in and enter. It was annoying to visit some of the casinos on the strip, but just to get 'thru' them, it would take at leaset 15-30 mins. that got old fast.Check out was 12, checked out by 11:30am. There were 3-4 ppl ahead of us, but no more than a 5 min wait. it was faster for us since we had pre-paid on the rooms. So overall, checkin-out was really fast.The casino/restaurants are in the next bldg over from the hotel. So its nice to not have that foot traffic thru the hotel. we did not eat at the hotel (thank god) We tried once to go eat there, but thought the Chinese dinner advertisement (thought it was a buffet) for $5.95 was poorly written. Instead it was $5.95 for 1 chinese entree. The staff there didn't care to explain after we had questioned the signs. I guess what you pay is what you get. So we left and went to PF Changs. That is the only negative experience I would report is with the casino restaurant (marilyn's).	
